{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514745"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:26:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:26:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12372"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12372"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.14,0.1,0.08,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4886"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102180"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4886"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12372"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84644"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"260"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"4656"},{"type":"tags","id":"4658"},{"type":"tags","id":"4923"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"9663"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7919"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8092"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26723"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35640"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39053"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102180"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents with a two day history of fever, chills and acute pain and swelling in his right knee. At the same time he noticed a rash comprising several small pustular lesions on his ankles. He does not think he has injured his knee. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes for which he takes metformin. He has poor compliance, with an HbA1C of 13% (3.5-6) recorded two months ago. On examination his blood pressure is 134/78 mmHg, pulse 72/min, temperature of 38.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 18/min and SpO2 98% on room air. His right knee is warm and swollen joint, with severe limitation to passive and active range of movement, and a negative patellar tap. The rest of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following initial investigations would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti Double-Stranded DNA","Anteroposterior and lateral knee X-ray","C-Reactive Protein","Serum uric acid","Blood culture"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation of mono-arthritis and a pustular rash is suggestive of gonococcal arthritis. It is often the result of bacteraemia caused by Neisseria gonorrhoeae. It is important to recognise this as a medical emergency that can result in significant morbidity and mortality if left untreated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis is generally established via positive\u003Cstrong\u003E blood culture \u003C/strong\u003Eor a combination of clinical suspicion, with positive genital culture associated with culture-negative arthrocentesis\u003Cstrong\u003E. \u003C/strong\u003EWhile arthrocentesis remains a key investigation, it is often culture negative in gonococcal arthritis and investigations for potential sepsis take precedence. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti Double-Stranded DNA\u003C/strong\u003E would be an important test to order when considering a diagnosis of systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), a chronic multisystem autoimmune disease. It is often associated with photosensitivity and can affect the liver, lungs and kidney.\u00a0 However, the rashes associated with SLE are usually in the form discoid lesions on arms and/ or a butterfly rash sparing the nasolabial folds. Joint pain in SLE is usually in the form of small joint polyarthritis rather than large joint monoarthropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKnee X-rays\u003C/strong\u003E are important in the evaluation of monoarthritis to exclude fractures, and can have added use in identifying the cause of chronic/recurrent arthritic disease (i.e. degenerative osteoarthritis, gout or advanced rheumatoid arthritis). However, an X-ray will usually appear normal in septic arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInflammatory markers, including \u003Cstrong\u003EC-Reactive Protein (CRP),\u003C/strong\u003E undeniably have a vital role in rheumatology; often as a biomarker for disease flares and severity. However, in this case it would be more important to consider a synovial aspiration over CRP as first line in investigating an acute monoarthropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum uric acid\u003C/strong\u003E estimation is an important investigation when considering the treatment of Gout, and is limited in its use for diagnosis. Gout is an inflammatory crystal monoarthropathy which presents clinically as severe pain that usually affects big joints, most commonly, the big toe (podagra) and occasionally the knee. \u00a0It is associated with yellow negative birefringent needle shaped crystals under polarising light and a serum uric acid concentration \u0026gt; 6.8 mg/dL. It is not associated with purpuric rashes. However, serum uric acid at the time of a monoarthritic presentation has little diagnostic yield as its often normal or even low in acute gout. A history of hyperuricaemia prior to a monoarthritic presentation dose favour gout. Serum uric acid levels are useful as a target for non-pharmacological \u0026amp; pharmacological urate-lowering therapy to prevent gout flares, and treat chronic tophaceous gout.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A combination of pustular rash with acute monoarthropathy warrants consideration of disseminated gonococcal infection.","Blood cultures are crucial in diagnosing disseminated gonococcal infection, especially when arthrocentesis is culture-negative.","Prompt identification and treatment of disseminated gonococcal infection can prevent significant morbidity and mortality."],"references":["Jagadeesan S, Shenoy P. Arthropathy in Dermatology: A Comprehensive Review. Indian Dermatol Online J. 2017 Mar-Apr;8(2):79-93. doi: 10.4103/idoj.IDOJ_25_17. PMID: 28405546; PMCID: PMC5372453. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28405546/","Seidman AJ, Limaiem F. Synovial Fluid Analysis. [Updated 2022 May 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537114/","Kgoebane K, Ally MMTM, Duim-Beytell MC, Suleman FE. The role of imaging in rheumatoid arthritis. SA J Radiol. 2018 Jul 11;22(1):1316. doi: 10.4102/sajr.v22i1.1316. PMID: 31754498; PMCID: PMC6837821. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6837821/","Shrivastava AK, Singh HV, Raizada A, Singh SK, Pandey A, Singh N, Yadav DS, Sharma H. Inflammatory markers in patients with rheumatoid arthritis. Allergol Immunopathol (Madr). 2015 Jan-Feb;43(1):81-7. doi: 10.1016/j.aller.2013.11.003. Epub 2014 Mar 20. PMID: 24656623. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24656623/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84644"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12372"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84644"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-10T08:39:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-10T08:39:57+09:30"},"relation